name: Le'Veon Bell
outlook: All signs indicated Bell is recovering from his injury and should be ready to go in 2016

history.2015: Bell began the season with a suspension and then experienced a season ending injury in week 8.
history.2014: Bell earned his reputation as the best runner in the NFL in the 2014 season.

name: Antonio Brown
outlook: Brown is expected to be one of the top wide receivers, and thus one of the top fantasy players for 2016

name: Odell Beckham Jr.
outlook: Beckham is an easy choice for a top wide receiver in 2016

history.2015: Beckham Jr had a great year.
history.2014: Beckham missed the first four games but finished the year on a strong note.

name: Julio Jones
outlook: Jones is an elite wide receiver talent. He gets a lot of targets and yards, but a relatively low amount of TDs for his production.

history.2015: Jones was the most targeted receiver in the league and had the most passing yards. Finished #2 overall to Antonio Brown.

name: Todd Gurley
outlook: Gurley is the one bright spot on a lackluster Rams team. Only his second season, yet all signs indicate he will be a first tier running back.

history.2015: Finished 5th overall despite not playing the first 3 games. Was able to put up both yards and touchdowns. Could have finished as top RB. 2015 NFL Rookie of the Year.

name: Cam Newton
outlook: While not necessarily expected to repeat a stellar 2015 outing, Newton is a bonafide elite QB and should be considered at or near the top of QB rankings.

history.2015: Newton was the top fantasy quarterback.
history.2014: Newton missed 2 games and played hurt in several others.

name: Aaron Rodgers
outlook: After an underperforming 2015 -- for the Packers as a whole, and thus Rodgers -- expect Rodgers to return to being his usual elite self. Expect lots of yards and touchdowns.

history.2015: Rodgers worst year so far -- mostly due to overall Packers injuries/dysfunction -- but still finished 12th overall.
history.2014: A typical Rodgers year where he finished as the #2 QB to Andrew Luck.
